Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Caption", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108],
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This Demonstration shows the implementation of a design for an infinite \
impulse response (IIR) low-pass digital filter. The input consists of the \
design specifications for the desired Butterworh analog filter. These \
specifications are used to determine the Butterworth (analog) filter transfer \
function ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"H", "(", "s", ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ", which is then mapped to the digital filter transfer function ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"H", "(", "z", ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ". The transformation of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"H", "(", "s", ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"H", "(", "z", ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " can be made using a bilinear transformation or impulse invariance. A \
number of plots are made available to examine different aspects of the final \
design result, such as the locations of the poles and zeros, the response of \
the filter to common test input signals, and the display of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"H", "(", "s", ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"H", "(", "z", ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " in symbolic form. Due to space limitations, the design is limited to a \
filter of order 10. You can get the design by asking for a minimum order \
filter or by specifying the filter order required. Both normalized units and \
hertz units can be used in the frequency specification."
}], "Text"]
}, Close]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Details", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108],
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108]],

Cell["\<\
Carry out the design by inputting the filter specifications using the \
sliders. There are five filter specification  parameters: \
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "samp"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is the sampling frequency;"
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "pass"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is the passband end frequency;"
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "stop"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is the start of stopband frequency; "
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["A", "pass"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is the attenuation in db at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "pass"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ";"
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["A", "stop"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is the attenuation in db at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "stop"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ".  "
}], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
The plot at the top-left helps you see the locations of these parameters. \
These are standard digital filter design parameters that can be found in a \
number of digital signal processing textbooks. \
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "You can do the design using normalized units (0 to 1) or in Hz. If you \
select normalized units, then 1 corresponds to the Nyquist frequency and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "pass"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "stop"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " will be between 0 and 1. Next select the analog-to-digital filter mapping \
method, which can be bilinear or impulse invariance. Next select the order of \
the filter. You can select a minimum order to be designed or specify the \
order yourself using the slider. The design supports a filter order up to 10. \
Finally, using the pulldown menu, select the plot type."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Some inputs will become disabled or enabled depending on what you select \
for the filter order and for the units. If you select a specific filter \
order, then only ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "pass"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " will be enabled, as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "stop"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is not required in this case; attenuation input is also disabled in this \
case, as attenuation ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["A", "pass"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " will be fixed at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"3", "db"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ". If you select normalized units, then the slider ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["F", "samp"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is disabled, as Nyquist is fixed at 1."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The design status is displayed below the main display window. Two possible \
design errors are detected and are displayed in red text. The first occurs if \
the filter order calculated is over 10 (when you select minimum filter \
order). In this case you need to change the design parameters until the \
filter order becomes less than 10. This error can occur if you select ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["A", "stop"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " much larger than ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["A", "pass"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ". The second error occurs if the gain is found to be too small. This can \
occur if you select ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
